        <div class="doc-content">
            <section class="doc-section">
                <h2>Overview</h2>
                <p>
                    Day 2 was where we moved from pure JavaScript into backend development.
                    We created our <strong>first Node.js server using Express</strong>. 
                </p>
                <p>    
                    We also went deeper into JavaScript concepts like scoping, functions, callbacks, and strict mode.
                    On top of that, we got introduced to NPM and how package managers and build tools work. 
                    Part of the exercise was setting up a Node.js project manually and understanding the role of the <code>package.json</code> file.
                </p>
            </section>

            <section class="doc-section">
                <h2>Clean Code: Strict Mode (and why it matters)</h2>
                <p>Strict mode helps catch mistakes that JavaScript normally just ignores.</p>
                
                <p>Example (bad practice): creating variables without declaring them:</p>
                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-js">
// "use strict";
// missing declaration type
// NEVER do this
totalGlobalVariable = "";
                </code></pre>

                <p>
                    This creates a global variable without you noticing it (easy to miss, hard to debug). 
                    But with strict mode enabled, this would throw an error.
                </p>
            </section>

            <section class="doc-section">
                <h2>Scoping in JavaScript: <code>var</code> vs <code>let</code></h2>

                <h3>Why <code>var</code> is risky</h3>

                <p><code>var</code> is function-scoped and can “bleed through” blocks, which can cause weird and surprising behavior.</p>

                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-js">
// block scope
{
    var someVariable = true;
    {
        var someVariable = false;
    }
    // someVariable is now false
}
                </code></pre>

                <h3>Prefer <code>let</code> (block scope)</h3>
                <p><code>let</code> is block-scoped, which means it makes code easier to understand:</p>
                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-js">
{
    let someVariable = true;
    {
        let someVariable = false;
    }
    console.log(someVariable); // true
}
            </code></pre>

            <h3><code>var</code> inside loops + async callbacks</h3>
            <p>When using <code>var</code> in a loop with callbacks (like <code>setTimeout()</code>) the callback sees the final value of <code>i</code>:</p>
            <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-js">
for (var i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
    setTimeout(() => {
        console.log(i);
    }, 1000);
}
            </code></pre>

            <p>Using <code>let</code> fixes this because each iteration gets its own block-scoped <code>i</code>:</p>
            <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-js">
for (let i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
    setTimeout(() => {
        console.log(i);
    }, 1000);
}
            </code></pre>

            <p><strong>Rule reinforced:</strong> Use <code>const</code> if possible, otherwise <code>let</code>. Avoid <code>var</code>.</p>
            </section>

            <section class="doc-section">
                <h2>Functions in JavaScript</h2>

                <h3>Hoisting</h3>
                <p>Function declarations are hoisted, meaning they can be called before they appear in the file:</p>

                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-js">
console.log(getRandomInt(4, 8));

function getRandomInt (min, max) {
    return Math.floor(Math.random() * (max + 1 - min) + min);
}
                </code></pre>

                <h3>Different ways to write functions</h3>
                <h4>1. Function declaration</h4>

                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-js">
function getRandomInt (min, max) {
    return Math.floor(Math.random() * (max + 1 - min) + min);
}
                </code></pre>

                <h4>2. Anonymous function expression</h4>

                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-js">
const getRandomIntAnonymousFunction = function (min, max) {
    return Math.floor(Math.random() * (max + 1 - min) + min);
};
                </code></pre>

                <h4>3. Arrow function</h4>
                
                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-js">
const getRandomIntArrowFunction = (min, max) => {
    return Math.floor(Math.random() * (max + 1 - min) + min);
};
                </code></pre>

                <h3>Callback Functions (Functions as First-Class Citizens)</h3>
                <p>
                    In JavaScript, functions can be passed around like values. 
                    We practiced this via a “generic action performer” that takes a name and an action (callback):
                </p>

                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-js">
function genericActionPerformer(name, action) {
    return action(name);
}
                </code></pre>

                <p>Example:</p>

                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-js">
function eatinAction (name) {
    return `${name} is eating`;
}

console.log(genericActionPerformer('Krelle', eatinAction));
// result: Krelle is eating
                </code></pre>

                <p>Example: anonymous function callback</p>

                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-js">
const runningAction = function (name) {
    return `${name} is running`;
}

console.log(genericActionPerformer('Krelle', runningAction));
// result: Krelle is running
                </code></pre>

                <p>Example: inline arrow callback (one liner)</p>

                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-js">
console.log(genericActionPerformer('Krelle', (name) => `${name} is laughing`));
// result: Krelle is laughing
                </code></pre>
            </section>

            <section class="doc-section">
                <h2>Build Tools & Package Managers: NPM + <code>package.json</code></h2>
                <p>
                    To start a Node project, a <code>package.json</code> file is created. 
                    This file keeps track of the project and the packages we install.
                </p>

                <h3>Initializing a Node project</h3>

                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-bash">
npm init -y
                </code></pre>

                <p>This command creates a default <code>package.json</code> file in the project.</p>

                <h3>Installing dependencies</h3>

                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-bash">
npm install express
                </code></pre>

                <p>This installs Express and adds it to the <code>dependencies</code> section in <code>package.json</code>.</p>

                <h3>What <code>package.json</code> is used for</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Describes the project</li>
                    <li>Tracks dependencies and their versions</li>
                    <li>Defines scripts that can be run with <code>npm run</code></li>
                    <li>Allows other developers to install the same dependencies using <code>npm install</code></li>
                </ul>

                <h3>Why <code>node_modules</code> should not be pushed to Git</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>It contains generated files from installed packages</li>
                    <li>It can always be recreated using <code>package.json</code> and <code>package-lock.json</code></li>
                    <li>The folder can be very large and will bloat the repository</li>
                </ul>

                <p>Instead of pushing <code>node_modules</code>, the folder should be added to <code>.gitignore</code>.</p>
            </section>

            <section class="doc-section">
                <h2>Creating the First Express Server</h2>
                <h3>Express setup</h3>
                <p>To create an Express server from scratch in <code>app.js</code>.</p>

                <p>Key steps:</p>
                <ol>
                    <li>Import Express</li>
                    <li>Instantiate the app</li>
                    <li>Define routes</li>
                    <li>Start the server on a port</li>
                </ol>

                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-js">
const express = require('express');
const app = express();
                </code></pre>

                <h3>Routes created </h3>

                <h4><code>GET /</code></h4>
                <p>Returns a welcome message:</p>

                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-js">
app.get('/', (req, res) => {
    res.send({ data: "Welcome to the first server!" })
});
                </code></pre>

                <h4><code>GET /snowstorms</code></h4>
                <p>Returns a warning message:</p>

                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-js">
app.get('/snowstorms', (req, res) => {
    res.send({ data: "Snowstorm is coming!" })
});
                </code></pre>
            </section>

            <section class="doc-section">
                <h2>Sending Data with GET Requests</h2>

                <h3>1. Path variables (route params)</h3>
                <p>Example route:</p>

                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-js">
app.get('/cars/:carModel/:year', (req, res) => {
    console.log(req.params);
    res.send({ data:`
        Your ${req.params.carModel} is very nice.
        Is it from the year ${req.params.year}?
        `});
});
                </code></pre>
                <ul>
                    <li><code>`:carModel`</code> and <code>`:year`</code> are dynamic values and come from the URL</li>
                    <li>These values are available in <code>req.params</code></li>
                </ul>

                <h3>2. Query string parameters</h3>
                <p>Example route:</p>

                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-js">
app.get('/bag', (req, res) => {
    res.send({ data: req.query });
});
                </code></pre>
                
                <ul>
                    <li>Data is sent after <code>?</code> in the URL</li>
                    <li>Example: <code>/bag?item=apple&amount=2</code></li>
                    <li>These values are available in <code>req.query</code></li>
                </ul>
            </section>

            <section class="doc-section">
                <h2>Running the Server</h2>
                <p>The server listens on port <strong>8080</strong></p>

                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-js">
app.listen(8080);
                </code></pre>

                <p>To run it locally:</p>
                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-bash">
node app.js
                </code></pre>
            </section>

            <section class="doc-section">
                <h2>Movies API - Part I (GET Only)</h2>
                <p>
                    As part of the ongoing REST API-exercises, a simple Movies API was implemented using Express.
                    The focus of this task was to design and implement the R (Read) part of CRUD, while strictly following REST conventions.
                    For this part, we kept it simple by not using a database or validation yet, and instead just stored the data in memory using JavaScript variables.
                </p>

                <h3>Implemented Endpoints</h3>
                <h4>GET /</h4>
                <p>Returns a welcome message to verify that the server is running:</p>

                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-js">
app.get('/', (req, res) => {
    res.send({ data: "Welcome to the Movie Server!" });
});
                </code></pre>

                <h4>GET /movies</h4>
                <p>Returns all movies in the collection:</p>

                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-js">

let movies = [
    { id: 1, title: 'Batman Begins' },
    { id: 2, title: 'The Dark Knight' }
];

app.get('/movies', (req, res) => {
    res.send({ data: movies });
});
                </code></pre>
                <p>This endpoint returns the full in-memory list, without any filtering or validation.</p>

                <h4>GET /movies/:id</h4>
                <p>Returns a single movie based on its unique ID:</p>

                <pre class="code-block"><code class="language-js">
app.get("/movies/:id", (req, res) => {
    const providedMovieId = Number(req.params.id);
    const foundMovie = movies.find((movie) => movie.id === providedMovieId);

    if (!foundMovie) {
        res.status(404).send({ errorMessage: `No movie found by id: ${req.params.id}` });
    } else {
        res.send(foundMovie);
    }
});
                </code></pre>

                <ul>
                    <li>The <code>id</code> is passed as a <strong>path parameter</strong> (from the URL)</li>
                    <li>The server controls the identifier (converts it to a number)</li>
                    <li>We don't assume anything special about how the movie object is structured - we just try to find it by its <code>id</code></li>
                </ul>
            </section>

            <section class="doc-section">
                <h2>Reflections (Day 2)</h2>
                <ul>
                    <li>Scoping rules (<code>var vs let</code>) explain a lot of "weird" JavaScript behavior</li>
                    <li>Callbacks are used everywhere in Node/Express, so understanding them early is important</li>
                    <li><code>package.json</code> + dependency management is the core part of any Node project</li>
                    <li>Express routing makes it simple to return data and handle inputs via params and query strings</li>
                </ul>
            </section>
